<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-10">
  <title>Week 10</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>
    <p>
      We now transition from point-set topology to algebraic topology. The central idea is to study
      topological spaces not just up to homeomorphism, but up to a coarser equivalence relation —
      <term>homotopy equivalence</term> — that retains enough geometric information for many
      applications while being far more flexible. The compact-open topology from last week provides
      a conceptual bridge: since the compact-open topology is always splitting, a homotopy (a
      continuous map <m>X\times[0,1]\to Y</m>) curries to a path in the mapping space
      <m>Y^X</m>. When <m>X</m> is locally compact, the exponential adjunction
      <m>X\times(-)\dashv(-)^X</m> makes this a perfect correspondence.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homotopy-of-maps">
      <title>Homotopy of maps</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-homotopy">
        <title>Homotopy</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces and let <m>f_0,f_1\colon X\to Y</m>
            be continuous maps. A <term>homotopy</term> from <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_1</m> is a
            continuous map
            <md>
              h\colon X\times[0,1]\longrightarrow Y
            </md>
            such that <m>h(x,0)=f_0(x)</m> and <m>h(x,1)=f_1(x)</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>. When
            such a homotopy exists, we say <m>f_0</m> and <m>f_1</m> are <term>homotopic</term>
            and write <m>f_0\simeq f_1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        A homotopy is a continuous one-parameter family of maps: at time <m>t=0</m> we have
        <m>f_0</m>, at time <m>t=1</m> we have <m>f_1</m>, and the map varies continuously in
        between. Using the compact-open topology, we can connect homotopies to paths in the
        mapping space <m>Y^X</m>. Since the compact-open topology is always splitting, a
        homotopy <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> curries to a continuous path
        <m>\hat{h}\colon[0,1]\to Y^X</m> with <m>\hat{h}(0)=f_0</m> and
        <m>\hat{h}(1)=f_1</m>. Conversely, if <m>X</m> is locally compact, then the
        compact-open topology is also conjoining, and every path in <m>Y^X</m> uncurries to
        a homotopy. For general <m>X</m>, however, the converse may fail: there can be paths
        in <m>Y^X</m> that do not correspond to homotopies.
      </p>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            It is sometimes important to require a homotopy to fix a subspace. If
            <m>A\subseteq X</m> and <m>f_0|_A = f_1|_A</m>, a <term>homotopy relative to
            <m>A</m></term> (or <term>homotopy rel <m>A</m></term>) is a homotopy <m>h</m> such
            that <m>h(a,t)=f_0(a)</m> for all <m>a\in A</m> and all <m>t\in[0,1]</m>. We write
            <m>f_0\simeq f_1\;\mathrm{rel}\;A</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-homotopy-equiv-rel">
        <title>Homotopy is an equivalence relation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            For any spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>, the homotopy relation <m>\simeq</m> is an
            equivalence relation on <m>\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            <em>Reflexivity.</em> The constant homotopy <m>h(x,t)=f(x)</m> shows
            <m>f\simeq f</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Symmetry.</em> If <m>h</m> is a homotopy from <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_1</m>, then
            <m>\bar{h}(x,t):=h(x,1-t)</m> is a homotopy from <m>f_1</m> to <m>f_0</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Transitivity.</em> If <m>h</m> is a homotopy from <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_1</m> and
            <m>h'</m> is a homotopy from <m>f_1</m> to <m>f_2</m>, then
            <md>
              h''(x,t) := \begin{cases} h(x,2t) \amp \text{if } 0\le t\le\tfrac{1}{2},\\
              h'(x,2t-1) \amp \text{if } \tfrac{1}{2}\le t\le 1, \end{cases}
            </md>
            is a homotopy from <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_2</m>. This is continuous by the gluing lemma
            (the two definitions agree at <m>t=\tfrac{1}{2}</m> since
            <m>h(x,1)=f_1(x)=h'(x,0)</m>).
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <p>
        The set of homotopy classes <m>[X,Y]:=\mathsf{Top}(X,Y)/{\simeq}</m> is one of the
        fundamental objects of algebraic topology. Homotopy is also compatible with composition.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-homotopy-composition">
        <title>Composition respects homotopy</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>f_0\simeq f_1\colon X\to Y</m> and <m>g_0\simeq g_1\colon Y\to Z</m>, then
            <m>g_0\circ f_0\simeq g_1\circ f_1\colon X\to Z</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>h</m> be a homotopy from <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_1</m>. Then
            <m>g_0\circ h</m> is a homotopy from <m>g_0\circ f_0</m> to <m>g_0\circ f_1</m>.
            Now let <m>h'</m> be a homotopy from <m>g_0</m> to <m>g_1</m>. The map
            <m>(x,t)\mapsto h'(f_1(x),t)</m> is a homotopy from <m>g_0\circ f_1</m> to
            <m>g_1\circ f_1</m>. Composing these two homotopies by transitivity gives
            <m>g_0\circ f_0\simeq g_1\circ f_1</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            These two lemmas together say that there is a well-defined <term>homotopy
            category</term> <m>\mathsf{hTop}</m> whose objects are topological spaces and whose
            morphisms are homotopy classes of continuous maps. This is the natural home for
            algebraic topology.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <example xml:id="eg-homotopy-basic">
        <title>First examples of homotopies</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Straight-line homotopy.</term> Let <m>f_0,f_1\colon X\to\mathbb{R}^n</m>
                  be continuous. Then <m>h(x,t):=(1-t)f_0(x)+tf_1(x)</m> is a homotopy from
                  <m>f_0</m> to <m>f_1</m>. In particular, any two maps into <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>
                  are homotopic.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Nullhomotopic maps.</term> A continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is
                  <term>nullhomotopic</term> if it is homotopic to a constant map. Every map into
                  <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is nullhomotopic.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Maps out of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.</term> The identity map
                  <m>\mathrm{id}_{\mathbb{R}^n}</m> is homotopic to the constant map at the origin
                  via <m>h(x,t)=(1-t)x</m>. This is a homotopy that "contracts" all of
                  <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> to the origin.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homotopy-equivalence">
      <title>Homotopy equivalence</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-homotopy-equivalence">
        <title>Homotopy equivalence</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is a <term>homotopy equivalence</term> if
            there exists a continuous map <m>g\colon Y\to X</m> such that
            <m>g\circ f\simeq\mathrm{id}_X</m> and <m>f\circ g\simeq\mathrm{id}_Y</m>. In this
            case we say <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are <term>homotopy equivalent</term> (or have the
            same <term>homotopy type</term>) and write <m>X\simeq Y</m>. The map <m>g</m> is a
            <term>homotopy inverse</term> of <m>f</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Every homeomorphism is a homotopy equivalence, but the converse is far from true. Homotopy
        equivalence is a much coarser relation: it identifies spaces that have the "same shape" in a
        flexible sense, even if they are not topologically identical.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-contractible">
        <title>Contractible space</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A space <m>X</m> is <term>contractible</term> if it is homotopy equivalent to a point,
            <ie />, if the identity map <m>\mathrm{id}_X</m> is nullhomotopic. Equivalently,
            <m>X</m> is contractible if there exists a point <m>x_0\in X</m> and a continuous map
            <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to X</m> with <m>h(x,0)=x</m> and <m>h(x,1)=x_0</m> for all
            <m>x\in X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example xml:id="eg-contractible">
        <title>Contractible spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is contractible: the map <m>h(x,t)=(1-t)x</m> contracts it
                  to the origin.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  More generally, any <term>convex</term> subset <m>C\subseteq\mathbb{R}^n</m> is
                  contractible. In particular, every disk <m>D^n</m> is contractible.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Any <term>star-shaped</term> subset of <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m> is contractible.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-noncontractible">
        <title>Non-contractible spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The spheres <m>S^n</m> for <m>n\ge 0</m> are not contractible (and in particular not
            homotopy equivalent to a point). The proof that <m>S^1</m> is not contractible
            requires the fundamental group or homology; we will be able to prove this in two weeks.
            That <m>S^0=\{-1,+1\}</m> is not contractible is immediate: it is disconnected, and
            contractible spaces are path-connected (hence connected).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-deformation-retracts">
      <title>Deformation retracts</title>
      <p>
        The most common way to prove two spaces are homotopy equivalent is to show that one
        <em>deformation retracts</em> onto the other.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-retract">
        <title>Retract and retraction</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A\subseteq X</m> be a subspace. A <term>retraction</term> of <m>X</m> onto
            <m>A</m> is a continuous map <m>r\colon X\to A</m> such that <m>r(a)=a</m> for all
            <m>a\in A</m>, <ie />, <m>r\circ\iota=\mathrm{id}_A</m> where
            <m>\iota\colon A\hookrightarrow X</m> is the inclusion. If such a map exists, we call
            <m>A</m> a <term>retract</term> of <m>X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <definition xml:id="def-deformation-retract">
        <title>Deformation retract</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A subspace <m>A\subseteq X</m> is a <term>deformation retract</term> of <m>X</m> if
            there exists a continuous map <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to X</m> such that
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li><p><m>h(x,0)=x</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>,</p></li>
              <li><p><m>h(x,1)\in A</m> for all <m>x\in X</m>,</p></li>
              <li><p><m>h(a,t)=a</m> for all <m>a\in A</m> and all <m>t\in[0,1]</m>.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </p>
          <p>
            Such a map <m>h</m> is a <term>deformation retraction</term>. If only conditions
            (1) and (2) hold — so that <m>r:=h(-,1)\colon X\to A</m> is a retraction and
            <m>\iota\circ r\simeq\mathrm{id}_X</m>, but the homotopy is not required to fix
            <m>A</m> pointwise — we call <m>A</m> a <term>weak deformation retract</term>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-deformation-retract-htpy-equiv">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>A</m> is a deformation retract of <m>X</m>, then the inclusion
            <m>\iota\colon A\hookrightarrow X</m> is a homotopy equivalence with homotopy inverse
            <m>r=h(-,1)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            We have <m>r\circ\iota=\mathrm{id}_A</m> (since <m>r</m> is a retraction) and
            <m>\iota\circ r\simeq\mathrm{id}_X</m> (via the deformation retraction <m>h</m>).
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <example xml:id="eg-deformation-retracts">
        <title>Deformation retracts</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Punctured Euclidean space.</term>
                  <m>\mathbb{R}^n\smallsetminus\{0\}</m> deformation retracts onto
                  <m>S^{n-1}</m> via <m>h(x,t)=(1-t)x+t\frac{x}{|x|}</m>. At <m>t=0</m> this is
                  the identity, and at <m>t=1</m> this is the radial projection
                  <m>x\mapsto x/|x|</m>. Points already on <m>S^{n-1}</m> are fixed throughout.
                  Thus <m>\mathbb{R}^n\smallsetminus\{0\}\simeq S^{n-1}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Möbius band.</term> The Möbius band deformation retracts onto its central
                  circle (an embedded copy of <m>S^1</m>), so the Möbius band is homotopy
                  equivalent to <m>S^1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Figure-eight neighborhood.</term> The open set
                  <m>\mathbb{R}^2\smallsetminus\{p,q\}</m> (the plane with two points removed)
                  deformation retracts onto a figure-eight — the wedge <m>S^1\vee S^1</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Cylinder.</term> The cylinder <m>X\times[0,1]</m> deformation retracts
                  onto <m>X\times\{0\}\cong X</m> via <m>h((x,s),t)=(x,(1-t)s)</m>. More
                  generally, for any subspace <m>A\subseteq X</m>, the product
                  <m>A\times[0,1]</m> deformation retracts onto <m>A\times\{0\}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Deformation retracts give us a useful way to think about homotopy equivalence geometrically:
        two spaces are homotopy equivalent when one can be continuously deformed into the other. The
        following proposition makes this precise.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-htpy-equiv-third-space">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Two spaces <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are homotopy equivalent if and only if there exists
            a third space <m>Z</m> containing both <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> as deformation retracts.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            The "if" direction is clear: if <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are both deformation retracts
            of <m>Z</m>, then <m>X\simeq Z\simeq Y</m> by
            <xref ref="lem-deformation-retract-htpy-equiv" />.
          </p>
          <p>
            For the "only if" direction, suppose <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> is a homotopy equivalence.
            One can show that <m>X</m> is a deformation retract of the <term>mapping
            cylinder</term> <m>M_f := (X\times[0,1])\amalg_f Y</m>, which is the pushout
          </p>
          <!-- TODO: PTX pushout diagram for mapping cylinder -->
          <p>
            <md>
              M_f := (X\times[0,1])\amalg Y\big/\!\sim, \qquad (x,0)\sim f(x),
            </md>
            and <m>Y</m> includes into <m>M_f</m> as the subspace <m>Y\hookrightarrow M_f</m>
            at the base. When <m>f</m> is a homotopy equivalence, both <m>X\cong X\times\{1\}</m>
            and <m>Y</m> are deformation retracts of <m>M_f</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homotopy-invariants">
      <title>Homotopy invariants</title>
      <p>
        A <term>homotopy invariant</term> is a quantity or structure assigned to topological spaces
        that is preserved by homotopy equivalences. We have already seen one.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-pi0-homotopy-invariant">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The functor <m>\pi_0\colon\mathsf{Top}\to\mathsf{Set}</m> descends to the homotopy
            category: if <m>f\simeq g\colon X\to Y</m>, then <m>\pi_0(f)=\pi_0(g)</m>.
            Consequently, homotopy equivalent spaces have the same number of path-components.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Let <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> be a homotopy from <m>f</m> to <m>g</m>. For
            any <m>x\in X</m>, the map <m>t\mapsto h(x,t)</m> is a path from <m>f(x)</m> to
            <m>g(x)</m> in <m>Y</m>. Thus <m>f(x)</m> and <m>g(x)</m> lie in the same
            path-component, so <m>\pi_0(f)([x])=\pi_0(g)([x])</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
      <p>
        Our goal over the remaining four weeks is to construct much richer homotopy invariants —
        the <term>homology groups</term> <m>H_n(X)</m> — that can distinguish spaces <m>\pi_0</m>
        cannot. For instance, <m>S^1</m> and <m>D^2</m> are both path-connected (so <m>\pi_0</m>
        sees no difference), but we will show <m>H_1(S^1)\cong\mathbb{Z}</m> while
        <m>H_1(D^2)=0</m>, proving they are not homotopy equivalent.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Wednesday</title>
    <p>
      Having established the language of homotopy, we now introduce one of the most important classes
      of topological spaces in algebraic topology: <term>CW complexes</term>. These are spaces built
      by iteratively attaching cells — a construction we already encountered when building spheres
      and projective spaces via pushouts in Week 3. CW complexes provide a class of spaces large
      enough to include all manifolds and most spaces arising in practice, yet structured enough that
      algebraic invariants (like homology) can be computed effectively.
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cell-attachment">
      <title>Cell attachment via pushouts</title>
      <p>
        Recall from <xref ref="notes-week-03" /> that a pushout in <m>\mathsf{Top}</m> glues two
        spaces together along a common subspace. The fundamental building block of a CW complex is
        the operation of <term>attaching an <m>n</m>-cell</term>: given a space <m>X</m> and a
        continuous map <m>\varphi\colon S^{n-1}\to X</m> (the <term>attaching map</term>), the
        space obtained by attaching an <m>n</m>-cell along <m>\varphi</m> is the pushout
      </p>
      <!-- Pushout diagram for cell attachment -->
      <p>
        <md>
          X\amalg_\varphi D^n \;:=\; X\amalg D^n\big/\!\sim, \qquad z\sim\varphi(z) \text{ for }
          z\in S^{n-1}=\partial D^n.
        </md>
        In the language of pushouts, this is the pushout of the span
        <m>X\xleftarrow{\varphi}S^{n-1}\xrightarrow{\iota}D^n</m>, where <m>\iota</m> is the
        inclusion of the boundary sphere into the disk. The image of the interior of <m>D^n</m> in
        the pushout is an <term>open <m>n</m>-cell</term>, homeomorphic to <m>\mathbb{R}^n</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        More generally, we can attach several <m>n</m>-cells simultaneously. Given a family of
        attaching maps <m>\{\varphi_\alpha\colon S^{n-1}\to X\}_{\alpha\in A}</m>, we form the
        pushout
        <md>
          X\amalg_{\{\varphi_\alpha\}}\!\left(\coprod_{\alpha\in A}D^n_\alpha\right)
          \;:=\; X\amalg\coprod_\alpha D^n_\alpha\Big/\!\sim, \qquad
          z\sim\varphi_\alpha(z) \text{ for } z\in\partial D^n_\alpha.
        </md>
      </p>
      <example xml:id="eg-cell-attachment-sphere">
        <title>Spheres via cell attachment</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The sphere <m>S^n</m> is obtained from a point <m>e^0</m> by attaching a single
            <m>n</m>-cell via the unique (constant) map <m>\varphi\colon S^{n-1}\to e^0</m>. The
            resulting pushout is
            <md>
              S^n \;\cong\; e^0\amalg_\varphi D^n \;=\; D^n\big/\partial D^n,
            </md>
            the disk with its boundary collapsed to a point. This gives <m>S^n</m> a CW structure
            with exactly two cells: one <m>0</m>-cell and one <m>n</m>-cell.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cw-complexes">
      <title>CW complexes</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-cw-complex">
        <title>CW complex</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>CW complex</term> is a topological space <m>X</m> equipped with a filtration
            <md>
              X^0\subseteq X^1\subseteq X^2\subseteq\cdots\subseteq X = \bigcup_{n\ge 0}X^n
            </md>
            constructed inductively as follows.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The <term><m>0</m>-skeleton</term> <m>X^0</m> is a discrete set of points
                  (the <term><m>0</m>-cells</term>).
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For each <m>n\ge 1</m>, the <term><m>n</m>-skeleton</term> <m>X^n</m> is
                  obtained from <m>X^{n-1}</m> by attaching a (possibly empty) collection of
                  <m>n</m>-cells. That is, <m>X^n</m> is the pushout
                  <md>
                    X^n \;=\; X^{n-1}\amalg_{\{\varphi_\alpha\}}\!\left(
                    \coprod_{\alpha\in A_n}D^n_\alpha\right)
                  </md>
                  for some family of attaching maps
                  <m>\{\varphi_\alpha\colon S^{n-1}\to X^{n-1}\}_{\alpha\in A_n}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The space <m>X</m> carries the <term>weak topology</term> (also called the
                  <term>colimit topology</term>): a subset <m>U\subseteq X</m> is open if and only
                  if <m>U\cap X^n</m> is open in <m>X^n</m> for every <m>n</m>. (If the
                  construction terminates at some finite stage <m>X=X^N</m>, this condition is
                  automatic.)
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
          <p>
            The letters "CW" stand for <term>closure-finite</term> (the closure of each cell meets
            only finitely many other cells) and <term>weak topology</term>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Each <m>n</m>-cell <m>e^n_\alpha</m> comes equipped with a <term>characteristic
            map</term> <m>\Phi_\alpha\colon D^n\to X</m> (the composite
            <m>D^n\hookrightarrow\coprod D^n_\alpha\to X^n\hookrightarrow X</m>) whose
            restriction to the interior of <m>D^n</m> is a homeomorphism onto the open cell
            <m>e^n_\alpha</m>, and whose restriction to <m>S^{n-1}=\partial D^n</m> is the
            attaching map <m>\varphi_\alpha</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <p>
        The pushout perspective makes the universal property of CW complexes transparent: a
        continuous map out of <m>X^n</m> is determined by a continuous map out of <m>X^{n-1}</m>
        together with continuous maps out of each <m>D^n_\alpha</m> that agree with the given map
        on <m>X^{n-1}</m> along the attaching maps. For finite-dimensional CW complexes, maps out
        of <m>X</m> are built by induction on the skeletal filtration.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cw-examples">
      <title>Examples of CW structures</title>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-sphere">
        <title>Spheres</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            As noted in <xref ref="eg-cell-attachment-sphere" />, <m>S^n</m> has a CW structure
            with one <m>0</m>-cell and one <m>n</m>-cell: <m>S^n = e^0\cup e^n</m>.
            Alternatively, <m>S^n</m> admits a CW structure with two cells in each dimension up to
            <m>n</m>: take <m>S^n\subset\mathbb{R}^{n+1}</m> with the <m>k</m>-skeleton
            <m>S^k\subset S^n</m> (embedded via the first <m>k+1</m> coordinates), where each
            <m>S^k</m> is obtained from <m>S^{k-1}</m> by attaching two <m>k</m>-cells (the upper
            and lower open hemispheres).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-projective-space">
        <title>Real projective space</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Recall from Week 3 that <m>\mathbb{R}P^n</m> is obtained from
            <m>\mathbb{R}P^{n-1}</m> by attaching a single <m>n</m>-cell. The attaching map
            <m>\varphi\colon S^{n-1}\to\mathbb{R}P^{n-1}</m> is the antipodal quotient
            restricted to the boundary of the upper hemisphere. This gives <m>\mathbb{R}P^n</m> a
            CW structure with exactly one cell in each dimension:
            <md>
              \mathbb{R}P^n = e^0\cup e^1\cup\cdots\cup e^n.
            </md>
            Taking the colimit, infinite real projective space <m>\mathbb{R}P^\infty</m> is a CW
            complex with one cell in each dimension <m>n\ge 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-complex-projective">
        <title>Complex projective space</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Similarly, <m>\mathbb{C}P^n</m> has a CW structure with one cell in each
            <em>even</em> dimension:
            <md>
              \mathbb{C}P^n = e^0\cup e^2\cup e^4\cup\cdots\cup e^{2n}.
            </md>
            The attaching map <m>S^{2k-1}\to\mathbb{C}P^{k-1}</m> sends a unit vector in
            <m>\mathbb{C}^k</m> to the complex line it spans — this is the Hopf map when
            <m>k=2</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-torus">
        <title>The torus</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The torus <m>T^2=S^1\times S^1</m> admits a CW structure with one <m>0</m>-cell, two
            <m>1</m>-cells <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, and one <m>2</m>-cell. The
            <m>1</m>-skeleton is a wedge of two circles <m>S^1\vee S^1</m>, and the single
            <m>2</m>-cell is attached along the loop <m>aba^{-1}b^{-1}</m>. One sees this from
            the standard identification of the torus as a square with opposite sides identified:
            the four corners of the square are all identified to the single <m>0</m>-cell, the
            edges become the two <m>1</m>-cells, and the interior of the square is the
            <m>2</m>-cell.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-graphs">
        <title>Graphs</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>graph</term> is a <m>1</m>-dimensional CW complex: it has a discrete set of
            <m>0</m>-cells (vertices) and a collection of <m>1</m>-cells (edges), each attached
            to one or two vertices. Loops (edges attached at both ends to the same vertex) and
            multiple edges between the same pair of vertices are permitted.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-surfaces">
        <title>Closed surfaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every closed orientable surface <m>\Sigma_g</m> of genus <m>g</m> has a CW structure
            with one <m>0</m>-cell, <m>2g</m> one-cells <m>a_1,b_1,\ldots,a_g,b_g</m>, and one
            <m>2</m>-cell attached along <m>a_1b_1a_1^{-1}b_1^{-1}\cdots
            a_gb_ga_g^{-1}b_g^{-1}</m>. The non-orientable surfaces admit similar descriptions
            with the appropriate identification words.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-subcomplexes-quotients">
      <title>Subcomplexes and quotients</title>
      <p>
        The pushout construction interacts well with the skeletal filtration, yielding several useful
        operations on CW complexes.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-subcomplex">
        <title>Subcomplex</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A <term>subcomplex</term> of a CW complex <m>X</m> is a closed subspace
            <m>A\subseteq X</m> that is a union of cells of <m>X</m>. Equivalently, <m>A</m>
            inherits a CW structure by taking <m>A^n=A\cap X^n</m>. A <term>CW pair</term> is a
            pair <m>(X,A)</m> where <m>X</m> is a CW complex and <m>A</m> is a subcomplex.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-cw-quotient">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>(X,A)</m> is a CW pair, then the quotient space <m>X/A</m> inherits a natural
            CW structure: it has the cells of <m>X\smallsetminus A</m> plus one additional
            <m>0</m>-cell (the image of <m>A</m>).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <example xml:id="eg-cw-quotient-sphere">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Taking <m>X=D^n</m> (one <m>0</m>-cell, one <m>(n-1)</m>-cell, one <m>n</m>-cell)
            and <m>A=S^{n-1}=\partial D^n</m> (the subcomplex consisting of the <m>0</m>-cell and
            the <m>(n-1)</m>-cell), the quotient <m>D^n/S^{n-1}\cong S^n</m> has the CW structure
            with two cells <m>e^0\cup e^n</m>, as expected.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The wedge sum and product also admit CW descriptions.
      </p>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-cw-wedge-product">
        <statement>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Wedge.</term> If <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are CW complexes with chosen
                  <m>0</m>-cells <m>x_0</m> and <m>y_0</m>, then the wedge sum
                  <m>X\vee Y:=X\amalg Y/(x_0\sim y_0)</m> inherits a CW structure.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <term>Product.</term> If <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are CW complexes, then
                  <m>X\times Y</m> has a CW structure whose cells are the products
                  <m>e^m_\alpha\times e^n_\beta</m> of cells of <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m>. (When
                  both <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> have finitely many cells in each dimension, the
                  product topology agrees with the CW topology; in general one must use the
                  compactly generated refinement.)
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-homotopy-extension">
      <title>The homotopy extension property</title>
      <p>
        One of the key technical advantages of CW complexes is their excellent behavior with respect
        to homotopies. The fundamental result is the <term>homotopy extension property</term>, which
        says that a homotopy defined on a subcomplex can always be extended to the ambient complex.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-hep">
        <title>Homotopy extension property</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A pair <m>(X,A)</m> of topological spaces has the <term>homotopy extension
            property</term> (HEP) if for every space <m>Y</m>, every continuous map
            <m>f\colon X\to Y</m>, and every homotopy <m>h_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to Y</m> with
            <m>h_A(-,0)=f|_A</m>, there exists a homotopy <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m>
            extending <m>h_A</m> with <m>h(-,0)=f</m>. In other words, the dashed arrow exists
            making the following diagram commute:
            <image width="50%">
              <description>
                The homotopy extension property diagram: <m>A</m> includes into <m>X</m> across
                the top, and both map down via <m>i_0\colon x\mapsto(x,0)</m> into the products
                with <m>[0,1]</m>. The map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> and the partial homotopy
                <m>h_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to Y</m> are given, and the HEP asserts the existence
                of <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  A \arrow[r, hook] \arrow[d, "i_0"'] \amp X \arrow[d, "i_0"] \arrow[ddr, bend left, "f"] \\
                  A\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r, hook] \arrow[drr, bend right, "h_A"'] \amp X\times{[0,1]} \arrow[dr, dashed, "\exists\, h" description] \\
                  \amp \amp Y
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-hep-retract">
        <title>HEP via retractions</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A pair <m>(X,A)</m> has the homotopy extension property if and only if
            <m>X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m> is a retract of <m>X\times[0,1]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Write <m>M_A := X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1] \subseteq X\times[0,1]</m> and
            let <m>j\colon M_A\hookrightarrow X\times[0,1]</m> denote the inclusion.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>(<m>\Leftarrow</m>)</em> Suppose <m>r\colon X\times[0,1]\to M_A</m> is a
            retraction, so <m>r\circ j=\mathrm{id}_{M_A}</m>. Given a map
            <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> and a homotopy <m>h_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to Y</m> with
            <m>h_A(-,0)=f|_A</m>, define <m>g\colon M_A\to Y</m> by
            <m>g|_{X\times\{0\}}=f</m> and <m>g|_{A\times[0,1]}=h_A</m>; these agree on the
            overlap <m>A\times\{0\}</m> since <m>h_A(-,0)=f|_A</m>. Then
            <m>h:=g\circ r\colon X\times[0,1]\to Y</m> is the desired extension:
            <m>h(-,0)=g(r(-,0))=g(-,0)=f</m> since <m>r</m> fixes <m>X\times\{0\}</m>, and
            <m>h|_{A\times[0,1]}=g\circ r|_{A\times[0,1]}=g|_{A\times[0,1]}=h_A</m> since
            <m>r</m> fixes <m>M_A</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            As a diagram, the construction is:
            <image width="55%">
              <description>
                Diagram showing the retraction-based construction of the homotopy extension.
                The retraction <m>r</m> maps <m>X\times[0,1]</m> to <m>M_A</m>, and then
                <m>g</m> maps <m>M_A</m> to <m>Y</m>. The composite <m>h=g\circ r</m>
                gives the extension.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  M_A \arrow[r, hook, "j"] \arrow[dr, "g"'] \amp X\times{[0,1]} \arrow[d, dashed, "h=g\circ r"] \arrow[l, bend right, "r"'] \\
                  \amp Y
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>(<m>\Rightarrow</m>)</em> Suppose <m>(X,A)</m> has the HEP. Apply it with
            <m>Y:=M_A</m>, with <m>f\colon X\to M_A</m> given by <m>f(x):=(x,0)</m>
            (the inclusion of the base), and with <m>h_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to M_A</m>
            given by the identity <m>h_A(a,t):=(a,t)</m>. These are compatible since
            <m>h_A(a,0)=(a,0)=f(a)</m>. The HEP produces an extension
            <m>r\colon X\times[0,1]\to M_A</m>, and by construction
            <m>r|_{M_A}=\mathrm{id}_{M_A}</m>, so <m>r</m> is a retraction.
          </p>
          <p>
            The forward direction as a diagram: we apply the HEP with target <m>Y = M_A</m>,
            <image width="55%">
              <description>
                The HEP diagram specialized to <m>Y=M_A</m>. The maps <m>f(x)=(x,0)</m>
                and <m>h_A(a,t)=(a,t)</m> are the identity embeddings into <m>M_A</m>,
                and the resulting extension <m>r</m> is the desired retraction.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  A \arrow[r, hook] \arrow[d, "i_0"'] \amp X \arrow[d, "i_0"] \arrow[ddr, bend left, "x\mapsto(x{,}0)"] \\
                  A\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r, hook] \arrow[drr, bend right, "(a{,}t)\mapsto(a{,}t)"'] \amp X\times{[0,1]} \arrow[dr, dashed, "r"] \\
                  \amp \amp M_A
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            and the dashed arrow <m>r</m> is a retraction since it restricts to the identity
            on <m>M_A</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
      <p>
        The upshot is that verifying the HEP reduces to a purely geometric problem: construct a
        retraction <m>r\colon X\times[0,1]\to X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m>. For cell
        attachments, this retract can be constructed explicitly.
      </p>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-disk-hep">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The pair <m>(D^n, S^{n-1})</m> has the homotopy extension property. Concretely,
            <m>D^n\times\{0\}\cup S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m> is a retract of
            <m>D^n\times[0,1]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Project radially from the point <m>(0,2)\in D^n\times\mathbb{R}</m> onto the subspace
            <m>D^n\times\{0\}\cup S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m>. This defines a retraction
            <m>r\colon D^n\times[0,1]\to D^n\times\{0\}\cup S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m>. The
            geometric picture: we project from a point "above" the cylinder onto its bottom face
            and lateral boundary. Here is an illustration in the case <m>n=2</m>:
          </p>
          <image width="65%">
            <description>
              The radial projection retraction for the pair <m>(D^2, S^1)</m>. The cylinder
              <m>D^2\times[0,1]</m> is shown with its bottom face and lateral boundary
              highlighted. A point <m>p=(0,2)</m> above the cylinder projects radially onto
              <m>D^2\times\{0\}\cup S^1\times[0,1]</m>, defining the retraction.
            </description>
            <latex-image>
              \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.8]
                % Cylinder lateral surface (back half, light)
                \draw[gray!40, fill=gray!5] (-1,0) -- (-1,2) arc(180:360:1 and 0.3) -- (1,0) arc(360:180:1 and 0.3);
                % Bottom face
                \draw[blue!30, fill=blue!10] (0,0) ellipse (1 and 0.3);
                % Lateral boundary (front half)
                \draw[red!60, thick] (-1,0) -- (-1,2);
                \draw[red!60, thick] (1,0) -- (1,2);
                % Top ellipse
                \draw[gray!60] (0,2) ellipse (1 and 0.3);
                % Lateral boundary (front half of top ellipse)
                \draw[red!60, thick] (1,2) arc(0:-180:1 and 0.3);
                % Bottom face outline
                \draw[blue!60, thick] (0,0) ellipse (1 and 0.3);
                % Point p above
                \fill (0,3.6) circle (1.2pt) node[above] {$p=(0,2)$};
                % Sample projection rays
                \draw[densely dashed, gray!70] (0,3.6) -- (-1,1.4);
                \draw[densely dashed, gray!70] (0,3.6) -- (1,1.0);
                \draw[densely dashed, gray!70] (0,3.6) -- (0.5,0);
                \draw[densely dashed, gray!70] (0,3.6) -- (-0.4,0);
                % Point on lateral boundary
                \fill[red!70] (-1,1.4) circle (1pt);
                \fill[red!70] (1,1.0) circle (1pt);
                % Points on bottom face
                \fill[blue!70] (0.5,0) circle (1pt);
                \fill[blue!70] (-0.4,0) circle (1pt);
                % Labels
                \node[right] at (1.15,1.0) {\small $S^1\times[0,1]$};
                \node[below] at (0,-0.45) {\small $D^2\times\{0\}$};
                \node[left] at (-1.4,1.0) {\small $D^2\times[0,1]$};
              \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-cw-hep">
        <title>CW pairs have the homotopy extension property</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>(X,A)</m> is a CW pair, then <m>(X,A)</m> has the homotopy extension property.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By <xref ref="prop-hep-retract" />, it suffices to show that
            <m>X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m> is a retract of <m>X\times[0,1]</m>.
            We build this retraction inductively over the skeletal filtration.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Step 1: single cell attachment.</em>
            Suppose <m>X=A\amalg_\varphi D^n</m> is obtained from <m>A</m> by attaching a
            single <m>n</m>-cell via <m>\varphi\colon S^{n-1}\to A</m>. Write
            <m>M_A := X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m>. The key observation is that
            taking products with <m>[0,1]</m> preserves the pushout structure: the
            cylinder <m>X\times[0,1]</m> is obtained by gluing
            <m>D^n\times[0,1]</m> to <m>A\times[0,1]</m> along
            <m>S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m> via <m>\varphi\times\mathrm{id}</m>:
            <image width="55%">
              <description>
                Pushout diagram showing that <m>X\times[0,1]</m> is the pushout of
                <m>A\times[0,1]</m> and <m>D^n\times[0,1]</m> over
                <m>S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}
                  S^{n-1}\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r, "\varphi\times\mathrm{id}"] \arrow[d, hook] \amp A\times{[0,1]} \arrow[d] \\
                  D^n\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r] \amp X\times{[0,1]}
                  \arrow[ul, phantom, "\ulcorner" very near end]
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
          </p>
          <p>
            By <xref ref="lem-disk-hep" />, there is a retraction
            <m>r_D\colon D^n\times[0,1]\to D^n\times\{0\}\cup S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m>.
            Define <m>r_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to A\times[0,1]</m> to be the identity. On
            the overlap <m>S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m>, both maps agree: <m>r_D</m> restricts
            to the identity on <m>S^{n-1}\times[0,1]</m> (since these points lie on the
            lateral boundary, which is fixed by the retraction), and <m>r_A</m> is the
            identity. By the universal property of the pushout, <m>r_A</m> and <m>r_D</m>
            assemble into a single continuous map <m>r\colon X\times[0,1]\to M_A</m>:
            <image width="70%">
              <description>
                Diagram showing how the retraction <m>r_A</m> on <m>A\times[0,1]</m>
                and <m>r_D</m> on <m>D^n\times[0,1]</m> assemble via the pushout
                universal property into the global retraction <m>r</m>.
              </description>
              <latex-image>
                \begin{tikzcd}[column sep=large]
                  S^{n-1}\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r, "\varphi\times\mathrm{id}"] \arrow[d, hook] \amp A\times{[0,1]} \arrow[d] \arrow[ddr, bend left, "r_A=\mathrm{id}"] \\
                  D^n\times{[0,1]} \arrow[r] \arrow[drr, bend right, "r_D"'] \amp X\times{[0,1]} \arrow[dr, dashed, "\exists!\, r"] \\
                  \amp \amp M_A
                \end{tikzcd}
              </latex-image>
            </image>
            Since <m>r_A</m> and <m>r_D</m> are both retractions onto their respective parts of
            <m>M_A</m>, the map <m>r</m> is a retraction of <m>X\times[0,1]</m> onto <m>M_A</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Step 2: induction over skeleta.</em>
            For a general CW pair <m>(X,A)</m>, write <m>X_k := A\cup X^{(k)}</m> for the
            union of <m>A</m> with the <m>k</m>-skeleton of <m>X</m>. Each
            <m>X_{k+1}</m> is obtained from <m>X_k</m> by attaching <m>(k+1)</m>-cells.
            By Step 1 (applied to each cell and assembled via the pushout over the
            disjoint union of attaching maps), the pair <m>(X_{k+1}, X_k)</m> has the HEP,
            so there is a retraction
            <m>r_k\colon X_{k+1}\times[0,1]\to X_{k+1}\times\{0\}\cup X_k\times[0,1]</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            Composing these retractions telescopically gives a retraction of
            <m>X_k\times[0,1]</m> onto <m>X_k\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m> for each
            finite <m>k</m>. For the passage to <m>X = \bigcup_k X_k</m>, we use the fact that
            <m>X</m> carries the weak topology with respect to the filtration
            <m>\{X_k\}</m>: a map out of <m>X\times[0,1]</m> is continuous if and only if its
            restriction to each <m>X_k\times[0,1]</m> is continuous. The retractions at each
            stage are compatible (each extends the previous), so they assemble into a retraction
            <m>r\colon X\times[0,1]\to X\times\{0\}\cup A\times[0,1]</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        The homotopy extension property has several powerful consequences, which we record as
        corollaries.
      </p>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-contractible-subcomplex">
        <title>Collapsing contractible subcomplexes</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>(X,A)</m> is a CW pair and <m>A</m> is contractible, then the quotient map
            <m>q\colon X\to X/A</m> is a homotopy equivalence.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Since <m>A</m> is contractible, there is a homotopy <m>h_A\colon A\times[0,1]\to A</m>
            from <m>\mathrm{id}_A</m> to a constant map. By the HEP, this extends to a homotopy
            <m>h\colon X\times[0,1]\to X</m> starting at <m>\mathrm{id}_X</m>. The map
            <m>h(-,1)</m> sends all of <m>A</m> to a single point, so it factors through
            <m>X/A</m>, and one checks this yields a homotopy inverse for <m>q</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-homotopic-attaching">
        <title>Homotopic attaching maps</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>\varphi_0,\varphi_1\colon S^{n-1}\to X</m> are homotopic attaching maps, then
            the resulting spaces <m>X\amalg_{\varphi_0}D^n</m> and <m>X\amalg_{\varphi_1}D^n</m> are
            homotopy equivalent.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Consider the space <m>X\amalg_{\varphi_0}D^n</m>. The homotopy between
            <m>\varphi_0</m> and <m>\varphi_1</m> can be used, via the HEP for the pair
            <m>(D^n, S^{n-1})</m>, to construct a deformation of the attaching region. The
            mapping cylinder of the homotopy between attaching maps contains both spaces as
            deformation retracts.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <example xml:id="eg-collapsing-tree">
        <title>Collapsing a maximal tree in a graph</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>\Gamma</m> be a connected graph (a <m>1</m>-dimensional CW complex). A
            <term>maximal tree</term> <m>T\subseteq\Gamma</m> is a contractible subgraph
            containing all vertices. By <xref ref="cor-contractible-subcomplex" />,
            <m>\Gamma/T</m> is homotopy equivalent to <m>\Gamma</m>. Since <m>T</m> contains all
            vertices, the quotient <m>\Gamma/T</m> has a single vertex, and each edge not in
            <m>T</m> becomes a loop — so <m>\Gamma/T</m> is a wedge of circles. If
            <m>\Gamma</m> has <m>V</m> vertices, <m>E</m> edges, and <m>T</m> contains
            <m>V-1</m> edges (as any tree on <m>V</m> vertices must), then
            <md>
              \Gamma\simeq\Gamma/T\cong\bigvee_{E-V+1}S^1.
            </md>
            In particular, <m>\Gamma\simeq\bigvee_k S^1</m> where <m>k=1-\chi(\Gamma)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cellular-maps">
      <title>Cellular maps</title>
      <definition xml:id="def-cellular-map">
        <title>Cellular map</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> between CW complexes is <term>cellular</term>
            if <m>f(X^n)\subseteq Y^n</m> for all <m>n\ge 0</m>, <ie />, <m>f</m> preserves the
            skeletal filtrations.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <p>
        Not every continuous map between CW complexes is cellular, but the following remarkable
        theorem — whose proof we will not give here — asserts that every map is <em>homotopic</em>
        to a cellular one.
      </p>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-cellular-approximation">
        <title>Cellular approximation theorem</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Every continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> between CW complexes is homotopic to a
            cellular map. Moreover, if <m>f</m> is already cellular on a subcomplex
            <m>A\subseteq X</m>, the homotopy can be taken to be rel <m>A</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem>
      <p>
        The cellular approximation theorem is analogous to the simplicial approximation theorem in
        combinatorial topology. It implies that for the purposes of homotopy theory, it costs nothing
        to assume our maps are cellular. We will make essential use of this when studying homology.
      </p>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-low-dim-homotopy">
        <title>Low-dimensional connectivity</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>X</m> is a CW complex with <m>X^n=X^0</m> for all <m>n\le k</m> (<ie />,
            <m>X</m> has no cells of dimension <m>1</m> through <m>k</m>), then every map
            <m>S^j\to X</m> with <m>j\le k-1</m> is nullhomotopic.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Give <m>S^j</m> its standard CW structure. By the cellular approximation theorem, any
            continuous map <m>f\colon S^j\to X</m> is homotopic to a cellular map
            <m>g\colon S^j\to X</m>. Since <m>g</m> is cellular, <m>g(S^j)\subseteq X^j</m>. But
            <m>X^j=X^0</m> is discrete and <m>S^j</m> is connected (for <m>j\ge 1</m>), so
            <m>g</m> is constant.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-suspension-and-cones">
      <title>Suspensions and cones</title>
      <p>
        Two constructions that arise frequently in algebraic topology — and that we will need for
        homology computations — are the cone and suspension.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-cone-suspension">
        <title>Cone and (unreduced) suspension</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The <term>cone</term> on <m>X</m> is the quotient
                  <md>
                    CX := X\times[0,1]\big/(X\times\{1\}).
                  </md>
                  It is the space obtained by collapsing one end of the cylinder
                  <m>X\times[0,1]</m> to a point (the <term>cone point</term>). The cone is always
                  contractible.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The <term>(unreduced) suspension</term> of <m>X</m> is the quotient
                  <md>
                    \widetilde\Sigma X := X\times[0,1]\big/(X\times\{0\}\cup X\times\{1\})
                    \;=\; CX\big/(X\times\{0\}),
                  </md>
                  obtained by collapsing <em>both</em> ends of the cylinder to points (the
                  <term>north</term> and <term>south poles</term>).
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <remark>
        <title>Reduced vs. unreduced suspension</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            If <m>(X,x_0)</m> is a <term>pointed space</term> (a space equipped with a chosen
            basepoint), the <term>reduced suspension</term> is the quotient
            <md>
              \Sigma X := \widetilde\Sigma X\big/(\{x_0\}\times[0,1]),
            </md>
            which further collapses the "longitude" through the basepoint to a point. Equivalently,
            <m>\Sigma X = X\wedge S^1</m>, the smash product of <m>X</m> with the circle (where
            <m>X\wedge Y := X\times Y/(X\vee Y)</m> is the quotient of the product by the wedge).
            The reduced suspension is the standard suspension in the context of stable homotopy
            theory and generalized cohomology.
          </p>
          <p>
            For CW complexes with basepoint a <m>0</m>-cell, the inclusion
            <m>\{x_0\}\times[0,1]\hookrightarrow\widetilde\Sigma X</m> makes
            <m>\{x_0\}\times[0,1]</m> a contractible subcomplex, so by
            <xref ref="cor-contractible-subcomplex" /> the quotient map
            <m>\widetilde\Sigma X\to\Sigma X</m> is a homotopy equivalence. In this course,
            we will primarily use the unreduced suspension <m>\widetilde\Sigma X</m>, since we
            are not yet systematically working in the pointed category.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <example xml:id="eg-suspension-sphere">
        <statement>
          <p>
            The suspension of <m>S^n</m> is homeomorphic to <m>S^{n+1}</m>:
            <md>
              \widetilde\Sigma S^n\cong S^{n+1}.
            </md>
            In particular,
            <m>S^n\cong\widetilde\Sigma(S^{n-1})\cong\widetilde\Sigma^2(S^{n-2})\cong\cdots
            \cong\widetilde\Sigma^n(S^0)</m>, where <m>\widetilde\Sigma^k</m> denotes the
            <m>k</m>-fold iterated suspension. Since <m>S^0=\{-1,+1\}</m>, this gives us an
            inductive construction of all spheres: each <m>S^n</m> is the suspension of the
            previous one.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        If <m>X</m> is a CW complex, then both <m>CX</m> and <m>\widetilde\Sigma X</m> inherit
        CW structures. For <m>\widetilde\Sigma X</m>: there are two new <m>0</m>-cells (the
        poles), and for each <m>n</m>-cell <m>e^n_\alpha</m> of <m>X</m>, the suspension
        contributes an <m>(n+1)</m>-cell <m>e^{n+1}_\alpha</m> to
        <m>\widetilde\Sigma X</m>. This observation will be essential when we compute the
        homology of spheres using the Mayer-Vietoris sequence.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-looking-ahead">
      <title>Looking ahead: from spaces to algebra</title>
      <p>
        We now have the geometric machinery — CW complexes, homotopy equivalence, and the homotopy
        extension property — to begin constructing algebraic invariants. Next week, we will define
        <term>singular homology</term>: for each space <m>X</m> and each integer <m>n\ge 0</m>, a
        group <m>H_n(X)</m> that captures <m>n</m>-dimensional "holes" in <m>X</m>. The key
        features of homology will be:
      </p>
      <p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Homotopy invariance.</term> If <m>X\simeq Y</m>, then
              <m>H_n(X)\cong H_n(Y)</m> for all <m>n</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Dimension.</term> <m>H_n(\mathrm{pt})=0</m> for <m>n\ge 1</m>, and
              <m>H_0(\mathrm{pt})\cong\mathbb{Z}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <term>Mayer-Vietoris.</term> For <m>X=A\cup B</m>, there is a long exact sequence
              relating <m>H_*(A\cap B)</m>, <m>H_*(A)\oplus H_*(B)</m>, and <m>H_*(X)</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
        Together with the CW structures we have built, these properties will let us compute
        <m>H_*(S^n)</m>, prove the Brouwer fixed-point theorem (stated without proof back in
        Week 2), and much more.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

</section>
